passages.name: B5NOTHING
passages.text:
"I'm always looking for new ingredients!" the Chef screeches. "You might find some nice things in Coffin City. If you do, bring them here and I'll cook it up for you!

"<<timedcycle .5s>>Now scram!<<becomes>><<endtimedcycle>>"

[[Next|B4]]

passages.name: LETTER
passages.text: Pity of The Wonders upon whoever or whomever may happen upon this, my last of notes. I can only assume that you are as unfortunate as I. My name is Felorius and I am a Paladin, sworn to uphold the gaze and glory of The Wonders. Upon this, the holiest of all possible missions, I had sworn to destroy that foulest of abominations, the <<display "WOMP">>. Undoubtedly created as a target to test the faith of the faithful, the <<display "WOMP">> must be destroyed! The <<display "WOMP">> is a creature of hatred for everything and everybody and cannot be redeemed. Killing the <<display "WOMP">> is also the only way you can ever leave the TOMBs of Reschette!\n<<set $LETTERREAD = 1>>\n[[Next|LETTER3]]

passages.name: B5ARROZ
passages.text:
<<set $GRUBS -= 1>><<set $SURVIVALISM +=1>>You give the grubs to the Chef, who sprinkles them on a board between two sheets of wax paper. The Chef then grabs a rolling pin and, with a sickening series of crunches, crushes them into a paste, and scrapes that into a pan with onions and butter. Adding seasonings and stirring, the Chef turns the heat down to low and covers the pan while preparing some rice. After about a half hour, the Chef hands you a steaming plate of arroz con gusanos, which you accept and eat with the grim resignation of the condemned.

 **Your survivalism has increased**

[[Back|B5MAIN]]

passages.name: C3GATE
passages.text: The gate is made of an ornate wrought iron in the shape of various creatures. There is a big, heavy [[padlock|C3PADLOCK]] holding it closed.\n\n[[Back|C3]]

passages.name: C2MUMMYFISTS
passages.text: You punch the Mummy! It feels like punching a punching bag! You do no damage!\n\n[[Next|C2MUMMYDEATH]]

passages.name: DARKDEATH
passages.text: It's so dark. It's so bad to be in a TOMB in the dark.\n\n[[Next|DARKDEATH2]]

passages.name: C2ZAMDEATH3
passages.text: It's not so bad: The Zambapta coos songs that are relatively on key, and tells you pleasant fairy tales, your favorite being the one about the encounter between a Bard and The Strega, one which ended with the wily Bard tricking The Strega into a trap which held her incarnation away from this world. \n\n[[Next|C2ZAMDEATH4]]

passages.name: A3DEATH2
passages.text:
The <<display "WOMP">> unfurls several probosci which pierce your skin in strategic places. Immedately preservatives and neurotoxins are pumped into your bloodstream at an alarming rate. Your blood vessels rupture and your heart explodes.

And the <<display "WOMP">> begins to feed.

 **YOU HAVE DIED**

<<display "SCORE">>

[[Retry|B3]], [[restart|RESTART]], or [[quit|QUIT]]?

passages.name: A3ADOPT
passages.text: Recognizing your responsibility, you scoop up the <<display "JOEY">> and begin to sing a little song. The <<display "JOEY">> makes a series of excited squeaks.\n\n[[Next|A3ADOPT2]]

passages.name: C3DJINN
passages.text: Many people have wondered what happened to the last Djinn in Reschette, but the truth is, there were two: They held onto each others' lamps, looked each other in the eye, and, taking deep breaths, wished.\n\n[[Back|C3RSCONCE]]

passages.name: ENDING3

Hello, young adventurer! I hope that you enjoyed your times in the TOMBs of Reschette -- you are the first adventurer to actually make your way through them alive, and for that you should be very, very, very proud!

But in addition to the gold and riches that you undoubtedly plundered from the TOMB, I hope that you managed to find the true treasures of the TOMBs of Reschette:

passages.text: Okay, you get your torch and you light the books on fire.\n\n[[Next|A4BURN2]]

passages.name: A1STREGA
passages.text: The witch-critter should have been less surprised: The Strega worked with magic and nature and pure cthonic creation: It shouldn't have been a surprise that The Strega's hut was //exactly// as the stories went. It was a strategy of disarmingness: Get 'em comfortable, The Strega figured, and then you can do whatever you want. It was one advantage of not having a dedicated temple or chapel: One could shift things to accomodate or disconcert every petitioner.\n\n[[Next|A1STREGA2]]

passages.name: C4MAIN
passages.text:
<<if $MIRROR eq 0>>You are in the Room of Mirrors. As far as the eye can see are mirrors, mirrors, mirrors, infinitely reflecting you. You wave at yourself. You look at your own back. You see yourself in mirrored chairs, mirrored tables, mirrored statuary -- and in the center of the room, reflected by nothing, covered in a fuligin cloak, is Vanity's Dowager.

[[Next|C4DOWAGER]]<<else>>You take it to be snow at first, but it's not cold. But what is this glittering dust? It is the remains of an infinite number of mirrors which have been turned into powder, too small to reflect anything but pure light. You leave before you are blinded by the dazzle.

[[Back|B4]]<<endif>>

passages.text: In the back of the room, in front of a gigantic pot, a distended creature is cooking onions.\n\n[[Next|B53]]

passages.name: B53

passages.name: C4DOWAGER4
passages.text: "If you've ever been possessed with nothing but the desire to see your own face, then truly the greatest punishment is to never know what that looks like. To never know who or what one //is//."\n\n[[Next|C4DOWAGER5]]

passages.name: C4DOWAGER5
passages.text: "I have been judged and punished. This is no curse. But it would be a curse if one were to stumble onto one's existence rather than walking headlong into it, wouldn't you say?"\n\n[[Next|C4DOWAGER6]]

passages.name: C4DOWAGER2
passages.text: "I gave up //everything// for this," Vanity's Dowager says.\n\n[[Next|C4DOWAGER3]]

passages.name: C4DOWAGER3
passages.text: "Listen, adventurer. Are you here for glory, or are you trying to accomplish something //noble// with the world? Because let me tell you, sometimes you can think one is the other, and that's how I ended up here."\n\n[[Next|C4DOWAGER4]]

passages.name: A4WORM
passages.text:
TOMB Worms

If you know one thing about exploring a TOMB, it's that you should never explore in the dark! Because TOMB Worms thrive in the dark, no one knows what one looks like, and the only people to have encountered them have never been seen again, having been devoured from the inside out. It's best to simply not interact with them -- just leave them alone and always carry a torch.

[[Back|A4BOOKCONTENTS]]

passages.name: A1STREGA3
passages.text: The tea smelled of moss, and earth--a strong puerh, a thick broth that the Witch-Critter was too nervous to ask about. //Be careful of anything The Strega gives you to eat or drink,// The Triad had said, //but don't outright refuse.// The Witch-Critter took a knife and, under the table, flayed open the skin of the left index finger, revealing a small metal probe--a modification granted by The Triad that the Witch-Critter had showed off before the mission.\n\n[[Next|A1STREGA4]]

passages.name: A1STREGA2
passages.text: The Witch-Critter wasn't saying anything at the moment, but was regarding a mug of tea that The Strega had poured into wooden cups that had sprung from the table, which was formed of a gigantic stump. Large toadstools formed underneath The Strega and the Witch-Critter, at The Strega's glance, and formed comfortable seats, and the branches at the top of the hut parted or clumpted together as necessary to let in or shut out light.\n\n[[Next|A1STREGA3]]

passages.name: A1STREGA5
passages.text: It //was// just tea, the Witch-Critter decided, and sipped--hot, and of the earth. Feeling cocky, the Witch-Critter waited a moment before speaking: //I have a message from The Triad.// And the Witch-Critter began to rattle off a list of demands, a list of The Strega's crimes, and a list of ways The Strega could make restitution.\n\n[[Next|A1STREGA6]]

passages.name: A1STREGA4
passages.text: The Strega, of course, saw all of this--saw the Witch-Critter dip the probe into the tea, and while The Strega couldn't see the internal processes, the vulgar methods of The Triad were obvious enough--in the Witch-Critter's brain, certain bits of circuitry mixed with flesh in order to analyze the composition of the tea. //Well, let them waste their time and their tech.// The Strega thought. //It's just tea.//\n\n[[Next|A1STREGA5]]

passages.name: A1STREGA7
passages.text:
And yet here The Triad were, in the form of a silly, arrogant messenger, full of self importance and with the conviction that The Strega's hut was a place of safety. The Witch-Critter was backed by The Triad, but The Strega didn't care about them. //You thought I would poison you, didn't you?// The Strega said, and the Witch-Critter smiled awkwardly mid-sip. Sensors in the Witch-Critter's face registered a chill in the air, augmented eyes noticed the light subtly darkening--imperceptible to natural eyes, imperceptible to The Strega, but obvious to a cyborg like the Witch-Critter. //I don't need to do that. I// am //Reschette.//

[[Next|A1STREGA8]]

passages.name: A1STREGA6
passages.text: It was getting tiresome, this standoff: It had been an age since The Strega had fashioned three children out of dirt, had grown moss and bark over them, had given them flowers for eyes and animated them with worms and parasites and had given them //life//, and while it had taken almost as long for The Strega to forgive the three for one by one leaving the Forest of Mystery and founding their own city, for augmenting their flesh with metal and machine, for proclaiming a gospel of progress, for taking a stance against nature, for advocating change for its own sake, for, in short, advocating the destruction of everything The Strega had ever worked for, The Strega //had// forgiven them, as much as a Wonder ever could forgive.\n\n[[Next|A1STREGA7]]

passages.name: A1STREGA8
passages.text: Later, interrupting a meeting between The Triad and another Witch-Critter, one petitioning for a socket in the arm in which memories could be stored and projected for the edification of everyone, a fox brought in a small bag. Inside the bag was a metal probe and a map to a field of flowers.\n\n[[Back|A1MAIN]]

Behold!

The Sarcophagus!

Inside this Sarcophagus, the dread Mummy of the Reschette!

passages.name: A2POUCH
passages.text:
<<set $POUCH = 2>>Inside the Holy Pouch is a quantity of white powder, which you smear onto a fingertip and rub on the inside of your ears.

Within moments a new clarity comes into your head. You grit your teeth and listen to the Acolyte's Haint, able to understand the words now:

[[Next|A2POUCH2]]

passages.name: C2MUMMYTORCH
passages.text:
You throw the torch at the mummy, who immediately bursts into flames!  

You see the shining gleam of the Reschette's soul being released; it hangs out for a moment near one particular niche in the back of the sarcophagus. Inside, you find a Holy Pouch!

<<if $TORCHES eq 2>><<set $TORCHES =1>><<set $MUMMY = 1>><<set $POUCH = 1>>While the Mummy is still burning, you quickly light the remaining torch!

[[Next|C2]]<<else>>Once the mummy fire goes out, it is pitch black.

[[Next|DARKNESS]]<<endif>>

passages.name: CSS eyes
A1UNDINE7
passages.text: The Undine had made attempts to leave the palace before and had been followed by members of the crowd. Before getting caught in the net, the Undine had managed to finally sneak out and live a life unseen by anyone -- all the Undine wanted was simple quietness, solitude. The fisher had ruined that, but the Undine //was// captivating. Resigned, the Undine stayed in the palace, finding roles for all of the crowd that had been seduced into service. The fisher did not gain anything like a place of honor -- few of the crowd did -- but it didn't matter. Proximity was honor enough.\n\n[[Next|A1UNDINE8]]

passages.name: DARKDEATH7
passages.text: Protected from the devastating effects of the sun, the TOMB Worms coordinate their wriggling and your body shambles out of the tomb and into town. For a few moments, no one notices anything. The TOMB Worms then unleash the hate that has been building up over time and spray it over the inhabitants of the town. The town is immediately crippled in the ensuing chaos. Finally, your body explodes, showering worms everywhere, which find their way to new hosts, distracted by neighborhood spats that have turned into all-out war -- and so the reproductive cycle of the TOMB Worm continues.\n\n[[Next|DARKDEATH8]]

Bats

DUSK!

With a creepy, tingling sensation, you hear the fluttering of leathery wings!

BATS!

With glowing red eyes and glistening fangs, these unspeakable giant bugs drop on to you and cause all sorts of diseases!

I have found that bats are way too scary to fight. The best you can hope to do is to have a high dexterity score or, barring that, some kind of protective magical amulet. Best of all is to avoid bats altogether!

All Undines are cursed with the ability to draw limerence from everyone they meet, and the fisher and the Undine were no exception. The fisher went to the same spot every day and cried out for the Undine, but the Undine did not hear. Lichs have not been seen in Reschette for many, many years, but rest assured, one could be plotting and planning as I write this! The lich represents a dilemma: An enchanter who decides on a goal that would take so many lifetimes to achieve that they decide immortality is the only way to achieve it. Little does the enterprising Lich realize that, upon class change, their XP caps and while they're able to develop the skills they already have, they're unable to learn new ones, and so many are frustrated. passages.text:
Haints

What more is there to say about a Haint? Who among us did not grow up in a hamlet, village, or castle that had at least one Haint knocking around? Most people are terrified of Haints, and that's because of the eerie Wail of the Haint. The Wail is simply the Haint trying to communicate. A dose of Holy Powder is helpful to attuning the ear to the frequencies of the Haint. Be warned: Haints are not Undead because they have no flesh -- they're beings of pure spirit who refuse to move on from the material plane.

passages.name: A4BEETLE
passages.text:
Citizen Beetles

Beetles achieved sentience in Reschette many years ago and successfully petitioned the Reschette at the time to form their own sub-nation. The Reschette, grossed out by anything from a different species -- which, incidentally, describes the majority of Reschette -- was only too happy to grant this request so long as they immediately left Castle Reschette and stayed out of sight forever. The Citizen Beetles rejoiced and formed the underground Reschette of Beetalia.  Citizen Beetles enjoy many civil rights, a strong economy based around dung, a vibrant arts community, and free democratic elections.

passages.name: A4MUMMY
passages.text:
Mummys

Mummys are tragic creatures indeed -- bound by a set of cursed rags which hold together rotting flesh and spirit, the average Mummy is the victim of a terrible fate. Mummys are not Undead because their spirit does not animate the flesh -- rather both are trapped inside the cocoon of rags which moves of its own volution. Only by burning the highly-flammable rags -- they're soaked overnight in Necromatic Kerosene as part of the preparation -- can the remains be destroyed and the soul liberated.

[[Back|A4BOOKCONTENTS]]

passages.name: A4ZAMBAPTA
passages.text:
Zambaptae

A Zambapta is another textbook example of Undead: A soul trapped in and animating their body after death, bound to the corpse by magic. While a Lich chooses their own fate, a Zambapta is not created voluntarily -- it is an enchantment placed on a person, usually as punishment.

Fun fact: The creation of a Zambapta involves similar spells as the creation of a Lich, and as a result Lichs are usually the only ones skilled and knowledgeable enough to cast them. During the Heydey of the Undeads, many Lichs would roam the countryside as itinerant carnifexes, performing Zambaptisms on prisoners.

passages.name: A4SKELETHON
passages.text:
Skelethons

Occasionally, when a strong emotion has permeated a place, the emotion can become sentient and find the nearest set of bones to possess. While one would think this would qualify your average Skelethon to be an Undead, it's actually not: The spirit of the skeleton's original owner has moved on, and so the emotion simply "takes up residence" in the abandoned bones similar to a hermit crab. Skelethons are not dangerous in and of themselves -- although one possessed by anger may be somewhat hostile -- and often serve as a personal and powerful example of sophisticated and complicated feelings. A popular children's stage show involved a series of Skelethons performing happiness, love, sadness, etc., until the skelethon personifying Greed and the one possessed by Vengeance teamed up with Meticulousness to sue the owner for exploitation.

passages.name: A4BOOKINTRODUCTION
passages.text:
Hello! My name is Felorious the Druid and this is my first book and it is all about the truth behind undeads, uncannies, and other critters!

There are some //Paladins// who would have you believe that all undeads are an abomination which must be destroyed. We druids don't believe such backwards things, but where the Paladins truly err is their confusing Undeads with Uncannies! Even a Druid might agree that there is possibly merit in releasing the spirit of an Undead from its fleshy prison, but most Uncannies are simply living their lives, just trying to make their way through the world like you or I. Too many Paladins, in their zeal, end up slaughtering innocent Uncannies in the name of their patron Wonder!

It is my hope that this book will help clear up misconceptions and confusions. As a loyal follower of The Strega, I hold all natural life as sacred. I have seen too much slaughter in my time and I'm writing this book to prevent more. I hope you enjoy reading it as much as I enjoyed writing it!

Love,
Felorius, The Druid
